column168: Description Of Events

XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2522 Visiomer Madame release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released to a 2’ x 6” area of the metal drum lid/body. The release was due to the drum having the incorrect bung cap placed on it. The bung was replaced with a new one and secured for shipment on. The impacted drums were wiped down with absorbent pads which were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: Member of our management team went to our unloads where the leaking hazmat was discovered. DescribePack: The box was wet from the leaking contents, The label itself was starting to fade away due to the strong chemical inside. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Immediately placed the package inside of a lined tote and took it to our hood vent to help stop the horrible smell to stop spreading.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived at hazmat during sunrise sort in a plastic bin. DescribePack: Inspection showed package to be wet from internal leakage, and fiberboard box is mostly lost or destroyed. Damage most likely caused from being dropped or mishandled. DurationRel: 12 and MitigateEffect: Remaining contents will be returned to shipper in a salvage drum, unless otherwise stated.

On the inside of the handle the seam is cracked about an inch or more. Hard to see the crack initially. The outer package was so damaged from the leak that the top half of the box was gone. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: There was no more leaking once package was found. Cleaned up any mess leftover and put all bottles upright in totes and put in hazmat cage.

column168: On March 1, 2024, four (4) 5-gallon pails of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of paint to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN1263-impacted trailer. All impacted material was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged in the R+L heat room for transport and disposal.
